attack we need to open a position first)} gxf6 12. Nh3 {(we need to attack an
opponent's weaknesses. That's why the knight goes to f4, where it puts the
pressure e6, g6 and h5.)} h5 13. Qg3 Qf7 14. Nf4 Rg8 15. Qe3 {(an attack again.
The principle of time says that we should try to attack with every move.)} Kd8
16. O-O-O Bd7 17. Be2 {(It is the only direct attacking move. You can see how
easily white can find the right moves.)} Rh8 18. Bf3 {(when an immediate
attack is not possible, we need to bring the least active piece into the
attack. White is preparing Rhe1.)} Nc6 19. Qe2 Be8 20. Rhe1 Kd7 21. Na4 {(it
is a logical move, because we should move our pieces forward on an opponent's
territory. However white had more powerful way.)} (21. Ncxd5 $1 {(we should
looks at ALL the forcing moves on the opponent's territory first of all. Here
it is very natural to sacrifice a knight, because it helps white to open the
position.)} exd5 22. Bxd5 $18) 21... Rd8 22. Nc5+ Kc8 {(If you are looking for
the forcing moves, then you will calculate 23.Ne6 and 23.Na6 first of all.)}
23. Nxa6 bxa6 24. Qxa6+ Kd7 25. Nxe6 {(another positional sacrifice helps
white to completely open the position.)} Qxe6 (25... Nxe6 26. Bxd5 $18) 26.
Rxe6 Kxe6 27. Re1+ {(A check is the most forcing move)} Kf7 28. Rxe8 Nb8 29.
