Bh6 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Nd5 {? (white makes the second move with the knight. It
breaks the principle of development. Here black should start thinking how to
attack.)} Nxd5 11. exd5 Qe7+ {(Do you remember the question "what else?" from
another lesson? In general we should make forcing moves and a check is the
most forcing way.)} 12. Be2 Nb4 {(an attack)} 13. c4 Bf5 {! (black is still
attacking. It looks impossible, because of Qa4. However let's remember another
thinking rule: if something looks impossible - you should try to figure out
how to do it anyway.)} 14. Qa4+ Kf8 15. Qxb4 Re8 {(Black sacrificed the knight,
but it allowed him to bring all the pieces in the attack. The principle of
time works well as usual.)} 16. Qd2 Rxg2 {(it's the only logical forcing move
on the white's territory)} 17. Kf1 $7 Rg3 (17... Be4 {(this should be better,
because we should keep the tension and don't move the pieces back.)}) 18. Qd1
Be4 {(if you focus the attention on the white's territory, you will realize
that Be4 is the only logical attacking move.)} 19. Rh2 f5 {! (if you have no
attacking moves at the moment, then you should prepare an attack on the next
move).} 20. Nxe4 fxe4 {(In fact white is playing without queen-side pieces.
That's why it is easily winning for black.)} 21. Bg4 (21. Bh5 Qg7 22. Rh1 e3
23. Qd3 f3 24. Qf5+ Kg8 25. Bxe8 e2+ 26. Kf2 Rg2+ 27. Kxf3 Qg3+ 28. Ke4 e1=Q+
29. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 30. Kd3 Rd2+ 31. Bxd2 Qxd2+ 32. Ke4 Qe3#) 21... e3 {(another
move forward)} 22. Bf3 (22. Be6 Qg7 $19) (22. Rg2 Qxh4 23. Rxg3 fxg3 $19) (22.
Qe2 Qe4 {#C5 f3#BB+}) (22. Qd3 e2+ {!} 23. Qxe2 Qg7 24. Qd1 Rxg4 $19) 22... Qg7
23. Rh1 Rg2 {(again if you focus the attention solely on the white's territory,
you will find Rg2 easily)} 0-1

